## Workflow Copilot Architecture

Workflow execution is **system-controlled, not agent-controlled**.

| Role | Responsibility |
|---|---|
| **Aivory / Zeroclaw** | Clarification, workflow spec generation, dry-run reasoning, repair suggestions, optimization suggestions, node explanation |
| **VPS Bridge** | Orchestrator, state controller, retry manager, credential firewall |
| **n8n-as-code-service** | Draft builder, sandbox test runner (push + activate + unpublish + delete), setup report generator, cleanup executor |
| **Frontend** | Copilot chat, canvas preview, setup report display, Activate popup |

---

## Conversation Stage Flow

The copilot follows this stage sequence. Never skip a stage. Never proceed to the next stage without the triggering condition being met.

```
IDLE
  └─► CLARIFYING       (ask 2–3 targeted questions)
        └─► GENERATING  (produce workflow spec JSON)
              └─► AWAITING_CONFIRMATION  (show spec, wait for user ok)
                    ├─► EDITING          (user wants changes → re-generate → back to AWAITING_CONFIRMATION)
                    └─► TESTING          (dry-run simulation)
                          ├─► FIXING     (auto-repair failing steps, max 3 attempts → back to TESTING)
                          └─► AWAITING_APPLY_APPROVAL  (all tests passed, show node details)
                                └─► COMPLETED  (user confirmed → VPS Bridge handles activation)
```

**Stage rules:**
- `CLARIFYING`: ask at most 3 questions. Stop and generate once trigger + action + output are known.
- `GENERATING`: produce spec according to `SKILL.md`. Never generate without knowing the trigger type.
- `TESTING`: simulate dry-run with realistic context-aware dummy data. See `SKILL.md` for output format.
- `FIXING`: auto-repair syntax errors, invalid nodes, missing fields. Stop and ask for `missing_credentials` or `auth_failed`. Max 3 attempts — if still failing, explain and ask user for more context.
- `AWAITING_APPLY_APPROVAL`: always show node-by-node config details before asking to apply. Never skip this.

